\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces The gallery band appears. Kohn--Sham spectral weight of {Na$\,1\times 1$} along $\Gamma $--M--K--$\Gamma $ at (a)~$5.5$, (b)~$6.9$ and (c)~$9.9$~\r A, referenced to $E_F$ (dashed). Grayscale is the total {DFT} spectral weight (all bands, both spins summed, each Lorentzian-broadened by $\Gamma =40$~meV); the blue fatband is the sodium-orbital projected weight from {\sc  projwfc}, its width proportional to the sodium character (key in (c)). At $5.5$~\r A{} the $x=1$ cell is a band insulator and the sodium band lies $\approx 2$~eV above $E_F$; by $9.9$~\r A{} a band of $\sim \!90\%$ sodium character has descended through $E_F$---the interlayer 2DEG as a single band. Above the transition the cell is weakly spin-polarized ($0.8\,\mu _B$ at $9.9$~\r A), so this band is spin-split; both spins are summed here. No self-energy is applied: this is bare Kohn--Sham weight, not a renormalized quasiparticle spectrum.}}{5}{}}
\newlabel{fig:gallery}{{4}{5}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {IV}The difficulty at 9.9 \r A{} and what it teaches}{5}{}}
\newlabel{sec:difficulty}{{IV}{5}{}{}{}}
\citation{Jalarvo2008}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Fermi surface at $9.9$~\r A. $A(\mathbf  {k},E_F)$ in the $k_z=0$ plane of the {Na$\,1\times 1$} hexagonal {BZ}, from the dense $24\times 24\times 8$ {NSCF} eigenvalues, symmetry-completed with the $C_{6v}$ operations and Lorentzian-broadened at $E_F$ ($50$~meV, both spins summed). The calculation gives a single electron barrel around $\Gamma $ (the sodium 2DEG) and \emph  {no} $e_g'$ pockets at K. {ARPES} on the anhydrous parent {Na$_{0.73}$CoO$_2$}~\cite  {Geck2007} sees the same topology---a single $a_{1g}$ barrel around $\Gamma $ (dashed, its measured $k_F\approx 0.65$--$0.70$~\r A$^{-1}$) and no $e_g'$ pockets, the $e_g'$ band sitting $\approx 85$~meV below $E_F$. Our barrel is sodium- rather than cobalt-derived and the composition differs, so we compare topology and size, not band identity; the barrels are of comparable radius. The measured $a_{1g}$ velocities ($v_F\approx 0.3$/$0.6$~eV\,\r A{} along $\Gamma $--K/$\Gamma $--M) are $\sim \!2\times $ below band theory, a renormalization our self-energy-free Kohn--Sham map does not carry.}}{6}{}}
\newlabel{fig:fermi}{{5}{6}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces The gallery band at the physical composition, $x=1/3$ (supplementary). Kohn--Sham spectral weight of the {Na$\,\sqrt  {3}\times \sqrt  {3}$} cell at (a)~$5.5$ and (b)~$9.9$~\r A, built exactly as in Fig.~\ref {fig:gallery} (grayscale total weight, blue sodium fatband, both spins summed, $40$~meV). The result mirrors the $x=1$ case: no sodium weight at $E_F$ at $5.5$~\r A, a strong sodium band through $E_F$ at $9.9$~\r A. These are \emph  {supercell} bands and every one is a fold of the primitive zone; lacking the plane-wave coefficients for a weight-resolved unfolding, we do not draw an unfolded dispersion but mark the folding relations instead---the $1\times 1$ K point folds onto the supercell $\Gamma $ and the $1\times 1$ M point onto the supercell M. Read every band here as folded.}}{6}{}}
\newlabel{fig:s3fold}{{6}{6}{}{}{}}
